TASK 4:
      Create a checklist of safety precautions and tools needed before starting the PC assembly/disassembly process, and explain why each is important.



Safety: 
       Unplug PC and drain residual power -
                                           Prevents electrical shock and protects components from short-circuiting.
Safety: 
       Wear an anti-static wrist strap or ground yourself - 
                                                           Prevents electrostatic discharge (ESD) from destroying sensitive microelectronics.
Safety:
       Work on a hard, non-conductive surface - 
                                               Soft fabrics and carpets generate static; hard surfaces provide stability.
Safety: 
       Handle components by their edges -
                                         Avoids touching gold contact pins, preventing corrosion from natural skin oils and moisture.

==================================

Tool: 
     Magnetic Phillips #2 Screwdriver -
                                       Fits standard PC screws perfectly; magnetic tip prevents dropping screws into the case and causing shorts.
Tool: 
     Screw Organizer or Trays -
                               Keeps different screw types separated to prevent cross-threading during reassembly.
Tool: 
     Good Lighting (Lamp/Headlamp) - 
                                    Essential for reading small motherboard labels and spotting tiny components in the dark PC interior.
Tool:
     Microfiber Cloth & 90%+ Isopropyl Alcohol -
                                                Needed to cleanly remove old thermal paste from the CPU without leaving a conductive residue.
Tool:
     Zip Ties or Velcro Straps -
                                Essential for cable management, preventing loose cables from hitting fans and improving case airflow.


